label.value: Facial dysmorphism - macrocephaly - myopia - Dandy-Walker malformation

definition.value: Autosomal recessive facio-digito-genital syndrome is a very rare syndrome including short stature, facial dysmorphism, hand abnormalities and shawl scrotum.

label.value: obsolete_lipodystrophy due to peptidic growth factors deficiency

definition.value: Pulmonary capillary hemangiomatosis (PCH) is a rare form of pulmonary arterial hypertension (PAH, see this term) characterized by a capillary infiltration of the pulmonary interstitium, bronchioles and pleura leading to elevated pulmonary arterial resistance and right heart failure. PCH is potentially fatal.

label.value: obsolete_hereditary hypercarotenemia and vitamin A deficiency

definition.value: Pai syndrome is an idiopathic developmental disorder characterized by median cleft of the upper lip (MCL), midline polyps of the facial skin and nasal mucosa, and pericallosal lipomas. Hypertelorism with ocular anomalies are also observed, generally with normal neuropsychological development.

label.value: obsolete_familial clubfoot with or without associated lower limb anomalies

definition.value: 15q13.3 microdeletion (microdel15q13.3) syndrome is characterized by a wide spectrum of neurodevelopmental disorders with no or subtle dysmorphic features.

label.value: obsolete_isolated autosomal dominant hypomagnesemia, Glaudemans type

definition.value: Adult-onset dystonia-parkinsonism is a rare neurodegenerative disease usually presenting before the age of 30 and which is characterized by dystonia, L-dopa-responsive parkinsonism, pyramidal signs and rapid cognitive decline.

CARASIL is a hereditary cerebral small vessel disease characterized by early-onset gait disturbances, premature scalp alopecia, ischemic stroke, acute mid to lower back pain and progressive cognitive disturbances leading to severe dementia.
Cleft lip - retinopathy is an exceedingly rare association characterized by cleft lip and progressive retinopathy.
Blepharo-cheilo-odontic syndrome is an ectodermal dysplasia syndrome characterized by the association of abnormalities of the eyelids, lips, and teeth.

3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaric aciduria (3HMG) is an organic aciduria, due to deficiency of 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-CoA-lyase (a key enzyme in ketogenesis and leucine metabolism) usually presenting in infancy with episodes of metabolic decompensation triggered by periods of fasting or infections, which when left untreated are life-threatening and may lead to neurological sequelae.
